{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625919"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:30:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:30:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17046"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17046"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0,0.19,0.77,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9736"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75739"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9736"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17046"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61252"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22914"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23051"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75739"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EOral rehydration therapy is the cornerstone treatment for preventing dehydration in acute gastroenteritis. The World Health Organisation recommends a specific formulation of oral rehydration salts.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of oral rehydration solution?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduces intestinal motility","Neutralises bacterial toxins","Directly stimulates intestinal water channels","Couples sodium and glucose absorption via cotransporter","Increases intestinal mucus production"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOral rehydration solution works through \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoupling sodium and glucose absorption via cotransporter\u003C/strong\u003E proteins in the small intestine. This sodium-glucose cotransporter (SGLT1) actively transports both sodium and glucose across the intestinal epithelium. Water then follows passively along the osmotic gradient created by this solute movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces intestinal motility\u003C/strong\u003E: while diarrhoea often involves increased intestinal motility, oral rehydration solution does not work by affecting gut movement. Antimotility agents like loperamide work through this mechanism, but oral rehydration solution focuses on replacing fluid losses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeutralises bacterial toxins\u003C/strong\u003E: oral rehydration solution does not interact with bacterial toxins which may be the cause of diarrhoea. It provides an alternative absorption pathway that continues to function despite the presence of toxins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly stimulates intestinal water channel: \u003C/strong\u003Ewater channels (aquaporins) are not affected by oral rehydration solution. Water follows sodium and glucose passively through osmosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases intestinal mucus production\u003C/strong\u003E: oral rehydration solution does not affect mucus secretion. The solution works through the epithelial cells themselves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis coupled transport mechanism remains functional even during secretory diarrhoea. The glucose-to-sodium ratio is carefully balanced to optimise absorption.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oral rehydration salts work by coupling sodium and glucose absorption in the small intestine through the sodium-glucose cotransporter.","The optimal ratio of glucose to sodium in oral rehydration solution is approximately 1:1 to maximise absorption.","Oral rehydration therapy prevents dehydration by promoting water absorption that follows the osmotic gradient created by sodium and glucose transport."],"references":["Oral rehydration salts. World Health Organization. January 1, 2016. Available from: https://www.who.int/publications/i/item/WHO-FCH-CAH-06.1","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61252"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17046"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61252"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-31T12:36:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-31T12:36:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9736"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75739"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag